Article.Abstract: Despite worldwide eradication of naturally occurring variola virus, smallpox remains a potential threat to both civilian and military populations. New, safe smallpox vaccines are being developed, and there is an urgent need for methods to evaluate vaccine efficacy after immunization. Here we report the identification of an immunodominant HLA-A*0201-restricted epitope that is recognized by cytotoxic CD8(+) T cells and conserved among Orthopoxvirus species including variola virus. This finding has permitted analysis and monitoring of epitope-specific T cell responses after immunization and demonstration of the identified T cell specificity in an A*0201-positive human donor. Vaccination of transgenic mice allowed us to compare the immunogenicity of several vaccinia viruses including highly attenuated, replication-deficient modified vaccinia virus Ankara (MVA). MVA vaccines elicited levels of CD8(+) T cell responses that were comparable to those induced by the replication-competent vaccinia virus strains. Finally, we demonstrate that MVA vaccination is fully protective against a lethal respiratory challenge with virulent vaccinia virus strain Western Reserve. Our data provide a basis to rationally estimate immunogenicity of safe, second-generation poxvirus vaccines and suggest that MVA may be a suitable candidate.
Article.ArticleTitle: Identification of vaccinia virus epitope-specific HLA-A*0201-restricted T cells and comparative analysis of smallpox vaccines.

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: Transgenic HHD +/+ B2m -/- Db -/- mice were used for immunizations. T-cell responses were monitored 10 days post-vaccination.

PBMCs were derived from a person immunized against smallpox at childhood. Human HLA-A*0201-restricted VP35#1-specific T-cells were generated from PBMCs by repetitive stimulation with VP35#1 peptide-pulsed mature monocyte-derived dendritic cells.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: Repeated stimulation of PBMCs with VP35#1-pulsed dendritic cells resulted in the expansion of A*0201/VP35#1-binding CD8+ cells (78.1%).

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: PBMCs were derived from a person immunized against smallpox at childhood. Human HLA-A*0201-restricted VP35#1-specific T-cells were generated from PBMCs by repetitive stimulation with VP35#1 peptide-pulsed mature monocyte-derived dendritic cells. Cytotoxic capacities of these cells were then assessed by co-incubation with VP35#1-pulsed T2 cells.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: VP35#1-pulsed T2 cells were lysed by PBMCs derived from a smallpox immunized person.

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: Transgenic HHD +/+ B2m -/- Db -/- mice were used for immunizations.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: Animals were challenged with vaccinia virus strain WR (2500000 pfu, intranasally) two weeks after vaccine (MVA) or three weeks after VP53#1 immunization. All animals inoculated with vaccine (10000000 IU) were protected, however, mice immunized with VP35#1 or mock-immunized were dead by day 9 suggesting that VP35#1 immunization, despite its potent induction of epitope-specific CD8+ T-cells, was insufficient to protect against infection with WR.

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: Transgenic HHD +/+ B2m -/- Db -/- mice were used for immunizations. T-cell responses were monitored 10 days post-vaccination.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: VP35#1 had a stimulating capacity for up to 0.7% of all CD8+ T-cells.

FirstInVivoProcess.DoseSchedule: 1 dose(s) of 0.1-0.5 ml of virus vaccine

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: Transgenic HHD +/+ B2m -/- Db -/- mice were used for immunizations. Intramuscular as well as intraperitoneal routes, different strains of smallpox vaccines (Wyeth, CVA and MVA) and various amounts of inoculants (250000 pfu of Wyeth or CVA, or 10000 - 100000000 infectious units of MVA) were used and T-cell responses were monitored 10 days and 6 months post-vaccination.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: Experiments using different smallpox vaccine strains (Wyeth, CVA and MVA), routes of immunization (i.m. or i.p) and amounts inoculated (250,000 pfu of Wyeth or CVA, or 100000-100000000 infectious units of MVA) resulted in activation of epitope-specific CD8+ cells. T-cell responses were initially monitored 10 days post-vaccination, however, a comparable response was demonstrated at 6 months.
